<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="213" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,1418,1731]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1454,1479]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small; head paler than the base of the tegmina (
<figureCitation box="[862,944,1454,1479]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1912,1934]" captionTargetBox="[288,1301,621,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[284,1304,607,1888]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 33. Lateral aspect of the nominate subgenus of Orthorapha (A – E) and subgenus Balsania (F – L). A – B, color varieties of O. laeta Jacobi; C, O. cassidioides Westwood, male; D, same, female; E, O. invidia sp. nov.; F, O. inflata sp. nov.; G, O. concinna (Stål); H, O. geminata (Jacobi); J, O. sagittata sp. nov.; K, O. reducta Walker; L, O. testacea Walker. Scale line: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217120/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[914,944,1455,1479]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
E). Head and tegminal tips tan; anterior half of tegminal costa white; pronotum of male and dorsum of female including clavi and adjacent part of tegmina sordid greenish; rest of tegmina, and legs of male, black (
<figureCitation box="[816,899,1526,1551]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1912,1934]" captionTargetBox="[288,1301,621,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[284,1304,607,1888]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 33. Lateral aspect of the nominate subgenus of Orthorapha (A – E) and subgenus Balsania (F – L). A – B, color varieties of O. laeta Jacobi; C, O. cassidioides Westwood, male; D, same, female; E, O. invidia sp. nov.; F, O. inflata sp. nov.; G, O. concinna (Stål); H, O. geminata (Jacobi); J, O. sagittata sp. nov.; K, O. reducta Walker; L, O. testacea Walker. Scale line: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217120/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[871,899,1527,1551]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
E) except for pale leg joints; vein tips scarcely indicated; tip of tegmina broadly rounded; hind wings as in 
<taxonomicName box="[826,998,1563,1587]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Ulopa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cassidioides">
<emphasis box="[826,998,1563,1587]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">O. cassidioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1014,1082,1562,1587]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1584,1606]" captionTargetBox="[276,1312,273,1556]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[265,1321,267,1560]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. New World Orthoraphini: habitus (A – B), hind wing (C – F) including detail of hamuli on costal margin (G – H), male abdomen in ventral aspect (J) and male genital capsule in lateral aspect (K). A, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) frontalis (Stål); B, F, H, O. cassidioides Westwood, female; C, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) obliqua (Jacobi); D, Orthorapha (Balsania) concinna (Stål); E, G, Orthorapha (Balsania) geminata (Jacobi); J, K, Orthorapha (Lepyronoxia) bufo (Walker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217115/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[1067,1082,1563,1587]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
F). Theca lamellate, broadest at midlength, tapered to minutely truncate tip (
<figureCitation box="[658,727,1598,1623]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 17" captionStartId="5.[151,264,918,941]" captionTargetBox="[217,1363,209,878]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,195,894]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 17. Male theca of Orthorapha s. s. (3 – 5), subgenus Balsania (6 – 7) and Lepyronoxia (8 – 17), lateral (A) and caudal aspect of tip (B): 3, O. cassidioides; 4, O. laeta; 5, O. invidia; 6, O. reducta; 7, O. sagittata; 8, O. obscurata; 9, O. inscripta; 10, O. decorata; 11, O. oculata; 12, O. bufo; 13, O. rana (type of O. glabrata); 14, O. subfasciata; 15, O. frontalis; 16, O. quadrimaculata; 17, O. sphaerata. Scale line: 0.05 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217116/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="213">
Fig. 
<number box="[713,727,1598,1623]" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Length: male 
<quantity box="[932,1023,1598,1623]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
, female 
<quantity box="[1122,1213,1598,1623]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
. Width across head 
<quantity box="[151,288,1635,1659]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" unit="mm" value="1.85" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.8">1.8–1.9 mm</quantity>
, across pronotum 
<quantity box="[492,578,1635,1659]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="213" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
greater.
</paragraph>
